Note the P-value of 2.2e-16 is not valid for the test. The hypotheses are \(H_0: a = 0\), \(H_a: a < 0\) Note that the tau3 values are not less than the calculated tau statistic \(-3.1431\), except for the \(10%\) level. Here we should take the conservative approach and build a model with a 1st difference. Thus at the 10% level we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Results of the Augmented Dickie-Fuller test say we need a first difference for the GISS temperature series.

That and looking at the plot, we can determine that the process is probably not mean stationary.

#Let’s look at autocorrelations and partial autocorrelations now

acf(gisTEMP, 100)

pacf(gisTEMP, 100)

Looking at the plots, perhaps a first difference is in order, and the PACF (autocorrelations) with a fairly quick decay, but significant lags staggered through the PACF plot leads me to believe we’ll need maybe one Moving Average component, and a seasonal Moving average component.

model0 <- Arima(gis0HOLD, order=c(1,1,1), seasonal=c(1,0,1), include.drift = TRUE)
acf(model0$residuals)

pacf(model0$residuals)

#Maybe we can do a little better. 
model1 <- Arima(gis0HOLD, order=c(1,1,1), seasonal=c(1,0,2), include.drift = TRUE)
acf(model1$residuals)

pacf(model1$residuals)

#Model2
model2 <- Arima(gis0HOLD, order=c(2,1,3), seasonal=c(2,0,2), include.drift = TRUE)
Acf(model2$residuals)

Pacf(model2$residuals)

#Slightly better! Maybe the PACF could be cleaned up slightly more, but one significant lag should be within tolerance.
#Let's look at the AIC and BIC value.

AIC(model0)
## [1] -2694.546
AIC(model1)
## [1] -2694.206
AIC(model2)
## [1] -2738.484
BIC(model0)
## [1] -2662.011
BIC(model1)
## [1] -2656.249
BIC(model2)
## [1] -2678.838

Both AIC and BIC point to model 2, which makes sense as it appears we have basically a white noise process left over. Now we have a model \(p=2, d=1, q=3\), and \(P=2, D=0, Q=2\). Let’s test the validity of the model with the Ljung-Box test:

#Ljung-Box test to determine appropriateness of the model:
Box.test(model2$residuals,30,type="Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  model2$residuals
## X-squared = 25.621, df = 30, p-value = 0.6943

\(H_0: \rho = 0\) for 30 lags, \(H_a: \rho \neq 0\) for 30 lags Note the p-value of 0.6943, there is not enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis, and we conclude that the autocorrelation for 30 lags is zero. So this is a good model with which to make predictions.

fore=forecast(model2, h=6)
foreSARIMA=fore$mean
upper = ts(fore$upper[,2], start=c(2019,6), frequency=12)
lower = ts(fore$lower[,2], start=c(2019,6), frequency=12)
windowDATA=window(gisFULL, start=c(2017,1))
plot(cbind(fore$mean, upper, lower, windowDATA), plot.type="single", col=c("BLUE", "RED","RED", "BLACK"), ylab="Forecast SARIMA")

#Check forecast accuracy with out of sample data

realDATA <- window(gisFULL, start=c(2019,7))
aSARIMA <- accuracy(realDATA, foreSARIMA[1:6])
aSARIMA
##                   ME       RMSE        MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set -0.06309164 0.08550633 0.06309164 -6.777301 6.777301

Results look pretty accurate.

Note the P-value of 2.2e-16 is not valid for the test. The hypotheses are \(H_0: a = 0\), \(H_a: a < 0\) Since the tau3 values are less than the calculated tau statistic \(-0.2035\) for all significance levels, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that there exists a unit root. Results of the Augmented Dickie-Fuller test say we do need a first difference for the atmospheric CO2 parts-per-million series.

Further note that the Box-cox value, 0.8027608, indicates very slight exponential growth in atmospheric CO2 concentrations. A log transformation of the data is not necessary.

We will use 13 and 17 lags for testing accuracy with out of sample data.

#Grainger causality test

#Grainger test for 13 lags
grangertest(gisHOLD ~ CO2HOLD, order = 13)
#Grainger test for 17 lags
grangertest(gisHOLD ~ CO2HOLD, order = 17)

Granger test results: We let \(\alpha\) be the coefficient for CO2, the null hypothesis \(H_0:\) \(\alpha_0 = \alpha_1 = ... = \alpha_{p} = 0\), and the alternative hypothesis \(H_a:\) Any one of the \(\alpha \neq 0\).

For both the 13 and 17 lag models we reject \(H_0\), and hence we can say an increase in atmospheric CO2 concentrations Granger-causes an increase in global average temperatures.

VAR13=VAR(X, p=13, type="const")
foreVAR13=forecast(VAR13, h=6)

We will just use the 14 lag model. Let’s use the Grainger causality test to check the validity of the model

#Grainger test for 15 lags
var<-VAR(X, p=14, season=12)
causality(var, cause = c("CH4HOLD", "diff.CH4CO2HOLD."))
## $Granger
## 
##  Granger causality H0: CH4HOLD diff.CH4CO2HOLD. do not Granger-cause
##  X.CH4TEMPHOLD.
## 
## data:  VAR object var
## F-Test = 1.8821, df1 = 28, df2 = 1089, p-value = 0.003761
## 
## 
## $Instant
## 
##  H0: No instantaneous causality between: CH4HOLD diff.CH4CO2HOLD. and
##  X.CH4TEMPHOLD.
## 
## data:  VAR object var
## Chi-squared = 1.0103, df = 2, p-value = 0.6034

Note I had to employ a different causality test for a multivariate set. Granger test results: We let \(\alpha\) be the coefficient for CO2, and \(\beta\) be the coefficient for CH4 (methane). The null hypothesis \(H_0:\) \(\alpha_0 = \alpha_1 = ... = \alpha_{p} = 0\) AND \(\beta_0 = \beta_1 = ... = \beta_{p} = 0\). the alternative hypothesis \(H_a:\) Any one of the \(\alpha \neq 0\) OR any one of the \(\beta \neq 0\).

For the 14 lag model we reject \(H_0\), and hence we can say an increase in atmospheric CO2 concentrations AND and increase in atmospheric CH4 (methane) concentrations Granger-causes an increase in global average temperatures. Further note, there is a test for instantaneous causality. We are not interested in this one.
